<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A huge fire continued today at the
nation's second largest petrochemical refinery after an explosion
ignited storage tanks holding millions of gallons of oil and
lubricants, killing one worker.
   A 4-square-mile area around the refinery, including a section of
Interstate 110, remained closed today.
   The blast shattered windows up to six miles away and was felt up
to 15 miles away. The fire sent a plume of thick, black smoke 500
feet into the air. Flames engulfed eight storage tanks holding more
than 4 million gallons of oil and lubricants, and two separator
units, which remove water from oil, officials said.
   It was believed ignited by a gas release, but what caused the
release was under investigation, said plant Manager Ed Galante.
